{"cursor":"4033","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"'Magnetospheric eternally collapsing objects' or 'MECOs' are proposed\nalternatives to black holes advocated by Darryl Leiter and Stanley\nRobertson. {{cite journal |author=D. Leiter, S. Robertson |year=2003\n|title=Does the Principle of Equivalence Prevent Trapped Surfaces From being\nFormed in the General Relativistic Collapse Process? |journal=Foundations of\nPhysics Letters |volume=16 |issue=2 |pages=143 |doi= 10.1023/A:1024170711427\n|id= |arxiv=astro-ph/0111421 }} They are a variant of eternally\ncollapsing objects or ECOs proposed by Abhas Mitra in 1998. {{cite\narxiv |author=A. Mitra |year=1998 |title=Final State of Spherical\nGravitational Collapse and Likely Sources of Gamma Ray Bursts |class=astro-\nph |eprint=astro-ph/9803014 }} Mitra had devised an ostensive proof\nthat black holes cannot form from the spherically symmetric gravitational\ncollapse of a star. Based on this, he argued that the collapse must be\nslowed to a near halt by radiation pressure. A proposed observable\ndifference between MECOs and black holes is that the MECO can produce its\nown magnetic field. An uncharged black hole cannot produce its own magnetic\nfield, but its accretion disc can. Astronomer Rudolph Schild claims to have\nfound evidence of such a magnetic field from the black hole candidate in the\nquasar Q0957+561. {{cite journal |author=R.E. Schild, D.J. Leiter, S.L.\nRobertson |year=2006 |title=Observations Supporting the Existence of an\nIntrinsic Magnetic Moment inside the Central Compact Object within the\nQuasar Q0957+561 |journal=Astronomical Journal |volume=132 |issue=1\n|pages=420â432 |doi=10.1086/504898 |id= |arxiv=astro-ph/0505518\n|bibcode=2006AJ....132..420S }}\n\nNeither ECOs nor MECOs have gained any significant acceptance among scientists;\nGerry Gilmore of the Institute for Astronomy at the University of Cambridge has\nstated that the concept is \"almost certainly wrong,\" {{cite web\n|author=I. Sample |date=30 July 2006 |url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/world/us-teams-quasar-probe-sinks-black-\nhole-theory/2006/07/29/1153816426971.html |title=US team's quasar probe sinks\nblack hole theory |work=The Age.com }} and the mathematician Chris Hillman\nhas stated that it is \"flat out wrong\". {{cite web |author=C. Hillman, J.\nBaez |date=17 August 2004 |url=http://groups.google.com/group/sci.physics.relat-\nivity/msg/4aafdaf243ae90aa? |title=Indian physicist vindicated in black hole\ncontroversy: Reply by John Baez |work=sci.physics.relativity }} Mitra's\nproof that black holes cannot form is based on the argument that in order for a\nblack hole to form, the collapsing matter must travel faster than the speed of\nlight with respect to a fixed observer. {{cite journal |author=A. Mitra\n|year=2000 |title=Non-occurrence of Trapped Surfaces and Black Holes in\nSpherical Gravitational Collapse: An Abridged Version |journal=Foundations of\nPhysics Letters |volume=13 |issue=6 |pages=543 |doi=10.1023/A:1007810414531 |id=\n|arxiv=astro-ph/9910408 }} Paulo Crawford and Ismael Tereno have cited\nthis as an example of a \"wrong and widespread view,\" and explain that in order\nfor a frame of reference to be valid, the observer must be moving along a\ntimelike worldline. At or inside the event horizon of a black hole, it is not\npossible for such an observer to remain fixed; all observers are drawn toward\nthe black hole. {{cite journal |author=P. Crawford, I. Terano |year=2002\n|title=Generalized observers and velocity measurements in General Relativity\n|journal=General Relativity and Gravitation |volume=34 |issue=12\n|pages=2075â2088 |doi=10.1023/A:1021131401034 |id= |arxiv=gr-qc/0111073 |bibcode\n= 2002GReGr..34.2075C }}\n","linknr":414,"url":"Magnetospheric_eternally_collapsing_object","recorded":1364162482,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Magnetospheric_eternally_collapsing_object&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Magnetospheric_eternally_collapsing_object&actio